PORT=
DB_URI=
JWT_SECRET=
STRIPE_API_KEY=
 When deploying to a server or platform like AWS, Railway, or Render, .env.example serves as a checklist of all environment variables you need to configure.
 For team collaboration — When a new developer joins and clones the repo, they won't have your .env file (it's in .gitignore). The .env.example tells them exactly what variables they need to create and set up on their machine.
For documentation — It acts as self-documenting configuration. Anyone can look at .env.example and immediately know what the app depends on.
For security — Your real .env with passwords, API keys, and secrets never gets pushed to GitHub. .env.example gives the structure without exposing anything sensitive.